// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
//  PMP EXAM MASTERY — MOCK TEST 4 (180 Questions)
//  Distribution: People ~42% (76q) | Process ~50% (90q) | Business ~8% (14q)
//  Exposed as window.PMP_MOCK_TEST_4
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
window.PMP_MOCK_TEST_4 = [

// ─────────────────────────── PEOPLE DOMAIN (~76 questions) ───────────────────────────
  { domain:'People', scenario:'A Scrum Master notices that the development team\'s daily standup has evolved into a 45-minute status meeting where team members report to the Scrum Master rather than coordinating with each other.', question:'What should the Scrum Master do?', options:['Accept the format since the team is communicating','Intervene to refocus the daily scrum: it is a 15-minute team synchronization event where team members coordinate with EACH OTHER (not report to the SM) on progress toward the sprint goal, impediments, and needed help. Coach the team to self-facilitate.','Cancel the daily scrum and replace with a written async update','Set a 15-minute timer and cut off the meeting when time expires regardless of content'], correct:1, explanation:'The Daily Scrum (standup) is a 15-minute team synchronization event, NOT a status report to the Scrum Master. When it becomes a status meeting, the SM has unintentionally created a traditional command-and-control dynamic. The SM should: refocus the event\'s purpose ("we plan together for the next 24 hours toward the Sprint Goal"), facilitate the team to address each other (not the SM), and step out of the questioning role. Cutting off the meeting without addressing the root behavior just adds frustration. The SM coaching the team to self-facilitate is the servant leadership response.' },
  { domain:'People', scenario:'A project manager is managing a virtual team. During a team retrospective, team members express that they feel isolated and disconnected from their colleagues, affecting their motivation and collaboration.', question:'What strategies should the PM implement?', options:['Tell the team that feeling connected is not relevant to project outcomes','Create structured social touchpoints: virtual coffee breaks, non-work conversation channels, team celebration rituals, virtual team-building activities, and "start the meeting with a personal check-in" practices — balancing work meetings with human connection','Hold in-person team events quarterly to compensate for virtual isolation','Hire a team coach to address the emotional wellbeing separately from the project'], correct:1, explanation:'Psychological connection drives collaboration quality, communication candor, and engagement in remote teams. Structured social practices (virtual coffees, personal check-ins, celebration channels) are not "soft" indulgences — they are measurable investments in team effectiveness. Research consistently shows that remote teams with strong social connections communicate more proactively, surface problems earlier, and maintain higher performance. The PM has a stewardship responsibility (PMBOK 7 Principle #1) for team wellbeing, especially in contexts where isolation is a known structural risk.' },
  { domain:'People', scenario:'A project manager assigns a complex analytical task to a team member who has strong technical skills but limited analytical experience. The team member delivers work that does not meet quality standards.', question:'According to situational leadership theory, what coaching approach should the PM use?', options:['Reassign the task to a more experienced team member','Provide a directive-coaching approach: give specific guidance on how the analysis should be done, explain the rationale, work alongside the team member on the first iteration, then progressively reduce direction as competence develops','Provide only motivational support since the team member has high commitment','Let the team member figure it out independently since they have strong technical foundation'], correct:1, explanation:'Situational Leadership (Hersey & Blanchard) aligns leadership style with readiness level. This team member has High Commitment/Low Competence on this specific task (Readiness Level 1 or 2). The appropriate style is Directing/Coaching — provide specific task guidance (WHAT and HOW), explain the reasoning (builds learning), work alongside in early iterations, then progressively delegate as competence grows. Pure motivation support (option C) is for high-competence/low-commitment situations. Pure delegation (option D) requires both high competence and high commitment. This prevents the failure of assignment-without-support.' },
  { domain:'People', scenario:'A project is in its final sprint. Three team members have received job offers from other companies and plan to leave after the project completes. Team performance has noticeably declined as members mentally transition to their next roles.', question:'What should the project manager do?', options:['Threaten to give negative references if performance doesn\'t improve','Have honest conversations acknowledging the transition, remind team members of the value of finishing strong (professional reputation, reference quality, colleagues who depend on them), accelerate critical knowledge transfer, and provide motivating closure activities (final team celebration plans, reference letters for strong finishers)','Accept the performance decline as inevitable','Immediately replace the departing team members with contract workers'], correct:1, explanation:'Mental transition (already thinking about the next job) is real and managing it requires honesty, not threats. The PM should: acknowledge the situation openly ("I know you\'re excited about your new opportunities"), appeal to professional values (how we finish matters for reputation and references), accelerate knowledge transfer NOW (not after departure notices are effective), and create positive closure incentives (team celebration, strong references for those who finish well). This approach converts the motivational deficit into a professional pride appeal — often highly effective in professionals who care about their reputation.' },
  { domain:'People', scenario:'A project team is working on a life-safety critical medical device. A team member raises a concern that a design decision may create a safety risk, but the concern is speculative and would require 2 weeks of additional testing to verify.', question:'What should the project manager do?', options:['Dismiss the concern as speculative since there is no hard evidence of a risk','Stop and evaluate the concern seriously: for life-safety systems, the burden of proof favors verification over speed. Conduct the 2-week testing to verify or dismiss the concern, escalate to quality and safety leadership, and document the concern and resolution in the risk register.','Continue development while the testing is conducted in parallel','Submit the device without testing and flag the speculative concern in the documentation'], correct:1, explanation:'For life-safety systems, PMI\'s ethics code and professional responsibility require that speculative safety concerns be taken seriously, not dismissed for schedule convenience. The 2-week verification investment is minimal compared to the cost of a real safety failure (patient harm, liability, regulatory action, brand destruction). Parallel testing (option C) may be workable depending on the risk — but only if the parallel work wouldn\'t be invalidated by the safety finding. Documentation without verification (option D) is negligent. This scenario tests: when schedule pressure and life-safety ethics conflict, ethics wins. Always.' },
  { domain:'People', scenario:'An agile team regularly achieves sprint goals but consistently fails to meet the Definition of Done for documentation. The team argues that documentation is not "real work" and slows them down.', question:'What should the project manager/Scrum Master do?', options:['Remove documentation from the Definition of Done to improve velocity','Facilitate a discussion with the team on WHY documentation is in the DoD (maintainability, onboarding, support team requirements), explore if the documentation standard can be streamlined without losing essential value, and if documentation is genuinely unnecessary overhead, remove it through proper consensus — but not because the team finds it inconvenient','Accept incomplete documentation since the sprint goals are being met','Make documentation a separate project outside sprint timebox'], correct:1, explanation:'Documentation resistance is common but requires exploration, not capitulation. The PM/SM should investigate: WHY is documentation in the DoD (regulatory requirement? onboarding? maintenance? support team)? Is the current documentation standard well-calibrated to actual need? If YES, it stays in DoD regardless of team preference — incomplete DoD means incomplete stories (which affects velocity calculation too, since incomplete stories don\'t count as done). If documentation standards can be streamlined without losing value, that\'s a legitimate retrospective action. "Real work" is anything that enables the deliverable to be sustainably useful — documentation often qualifies.' },
  { domain:'People', scenario:'Two members of the project team are from different cultural backgrounds. One values direct, explicit communication and the other values indirect, contextual communication. Misunderstandings are causing friction.', question:'What should the project manager do?', options:['Tell both team members to adopt a single standard communication style','Facilitate a cultural awareness session where both styles are explained and valued, establish explicit communication agreements for this project (e.g., "in our team, we always state expectations directly in writing after verbal discussions"), and coach team members to bridge cultural differences with curiosity rather than judgment','Separate the team members onto different workstreams to eliminate interaction','Have team members communicate through a third-party coordinator'], correct:1, explanation:'Cross-cultural communication differences are legitimate and require bridging, not forcing homogenization. The PM\'s approach: create psychological safety to discuss differences openly, extract the value of each style (direct communication = clarity and efficiency; indirect communication = relationship preservation and nuance), and establish explicit team protocols that reduce ambiguity (written summaries of verbal agreements, clear requests rather than hints). Cultural intelligence — adapting bridge practices without dismissing either style — is a professional PM competency and increasingly tested on the PMP exam.' },
  { domain:'People', scenario:'A project manager is having difficulty getting a critical team member to attend mandatory project meetings. The team member says they are "too busy" with other work.', question:'What should the project manager do?', options:['Remove the team member from the project and find a replacement','Have a private conversation to understand the specific competing demands, assess which meetings are truly essential vs. optional for this team member\'s role, explore solutions (shorter meetings, flexible timing, async alternatives for non-critical agenda items), and if the conflict is unresolvable, escalate the resource conflict to functional management with documented impact','Continue scheduling meetings without the team member and brief them afterward','Send escalation emails to the team member\'s manager immediately'], correct:1, explanation:'Meeting non-attendance has structural causes — competing priorities, poor meeting design, or genuine overallocation. The PM should diagnose: are these meetings genuinely essential for this person, or could their value be captured async? If attendance is truly mandatory (decision authority, technical expertise required), then the PM must resolve the competing demand conflict through functional management negotiation — with documented impact on project outcomes. Jumping to escalation before attempting a solution creates unnecessary conflict. Continuing without the team member may leave critical gaps in decisions.' },
  { domain:'People', scenario:'A project manager on a large infrastructure project is responsible for a team of 25 people. The PM tries to have a weekly 1:1 with each team member but finds it unsustainable.', question:'What team structure modification would be MOST effective?', options:['Eliminate all 1:1 meetings since large teams require only group communication','Create a team lead structure: identify 4-5 experienced team leads who each manage 4-6 team members directly, with the PM conducting regular 1:1s with leads and occasional skip-level connections with team members','Continue trying to meet 25 people weekly — it is a PM responsibility','Move all communication to group formats (daily standups, weekly team meetings)'], correct:1, explanation:'Beyond a team size of approximately 7-9 members, direct management of all team members by one PM creates unsustainable administrative burden and reduces management quality. A team lead / technical lead structure (the PM managing a layer of leads who manage individual contributors) is the standard organizational response. The PM maintains strategic oversight through lead 1:1s (5 leads × 30 min = 2.5 hours vs. 25 members × 30 min = 12.5 hours), conducts occasional skip-levels to maintain ground truth, and uses team-wide formats for project-wide communication. This is delegation and organizational design — a management competency.' },
  { domain:'People', scenario:'During a retrospective, team members begin personally criticizing each other rather than focusing on process improvements. The atmosphere becomes tense and unproductive.', question:'What should the facilitator (PM or Scrum Master) do?', options:['Let the criticism continue since retrospectives must surface all team tensions','Immediately redirect the discussion: refocus on behaviors and processes (not people), use structured facilitation techniques (what went well? what could improve? what action will we take?), call a short break to diffuse tension, and remind the team of retrospective ground rules (Vegas rule, positive intent assumption)','End the retrospective immediately to prevent further damage','Ask the criticized team members to leave the room while issues about them are discussed'], correct:1, explanation:'Retrospectives require psychological safety to be effective — personal criticism destroys it. The facilitator must act: briefly acknowledge the tension ("I notice this is getting personal — let\'s redirect"), refocus on behaviors and process ("what could we do differently?" not "what\'s wrong with X?"), and use structured formats that depersonalize feedback. Ground rules established at the beginning of retrospectives (or in the Team Charter) should include: attack problems, not people; assume positive intent; stay curious about root causes. A short break diffuses immediate emotional heat. Continuing personal attacks, ending early, or removing participants all damage future psychological safety.' },
  { domain:'People', scenario:'A project manager discovers that a team member has been padding their time reports, logging more hours than actually worked on project activities.', question:'What should the project manager do?', options:['Issue a formal warning immediately','Have a private conversation: present the specific evidence calmly, listen to the team member\'s explanation (there may be context the PM doesn\'t know), if fraud is confirmed — follow organizational HR and ethics protocols (formal warning, HR involvement, potential contract termination for contractors)','Ignore it if the project is within budget','Bring the issue up in the next team meeting to set a deterrent example'], correct:1, explanation:'Time fraud is a serious professional and potentially legal matter. The PM\'s process: (1) Verify the evidence is solid, not circumstantial. (2) Private, direct conversation — present specific evidence, listen to explanation (could there be a legitimate mistake? system error?). (3) If fraud is confirmed: follow organizational HR protocol (formal disciplinary process, documentation), escalate to HR, involve legal for contractors where applicable. Ignoring it violates the PM\'s financial oversight obligation. Public confrontation violates due process and confidentiality. This is governance and ethics enforcement — a PM accountability.' },
  { domain:'People', scenario:'A project team member who is the sole expert in a critical technology raises their estimate for a key deliverable from 2 weeks to 6 weeks, citing newly discovered complexity. This significantly impacts the critical path.', question:'What should the project manager do?', options:['Reject the revised estimate and hold the team member to the original 2-week estimate','Investigate the newly discovered complexity with the team member: is the additional time justified? Can the work be decomposed to identify which parts drive the extension? Explore options (additional expertise, scope reduction, parallel work) and update the schedule with the revised estimate if validated, communicating impact to stakeholders.','Accept the 6-week estimate without investigation','Replace the team member with someone who can deliver in 2 weeks'], correct:1, explanation:'A 3× estimate increase from the sole expert deserves investigation, not blind acceptance or blind rejection. The PM should: understand the specific complexity discovered (this may reveal a legitimate risk that needs risk register update), have the team member decompose the 6 weeks (which specific activities account for the increase?), assess whether alternative approaches could reduce time, check if other experts or tools could assist, and validate the revised estimate through a structured review. If validated, update the schedule and communicate impact. Rejecting without investigation assumes the expert is padding; accepting without investigation creates schedule risk. Investigation is the professional response.' },
  { domain:'People', scenario:'An agile project manager is leading a team that has been asked to integrate a legacy system with a new platform. The team has never worked with the legacy system. Three sprints in, technical complexity is proving much greater than anticipated.', question:'What should the PM do to address the escalating technical uncertainty?', options:['Force the team to work faster to compensate for underestimated complexity','Conduct a technical spike to deeply investigate the legacy system constraints, update the product backlog to reflect the actual complexity discovered, re-forecast the release timeline based on empirical evidence, communicate the revised forecast to stakeholders with transparency about what was unknown upfront, and consider whether specialized legacy system expertise needs to be added to the team','Terminate the project since the complexity is unmanageable','Hold the original commitment and manage stakeholder expectations privately'], correct:1, explanation:'Discovered technical complexity in agile projects should trigger: (1) A structured investigation (spike) to understand actual constraints before committing to more work. (2) Backlog refinement to add the newly discovered work items. (3) Velocity-based re-forecast (new timeline based on actual sprint evidence, not original estimates). (4) Transparent stakeholder communication — early transparency about a revised forecast is always better than late delivery surprises. (5) Skill gap assessment — does the team need specialized legacy expertise? This is empirical adaptation — the agile response to discovering unknown complexity.' },
  { domain:'People', scenario:'A PM is leading a team through a difficult project phase. Despite best efforts, the team misses a major milestone. Team morale is very low.', question:'What should the PM do FIRST after the missed milestone?', options:['Immediately create a recovery plan to focus the team forward','Acknowledge the miss transparently with the team: validate the difficulty, avoid blame, express confidence in the team\'s ability to recover, have a structured retrospective on root causes, and then co-create the recovery plan — moving from assessment to action with the team\'s involvement','Escalate to the sponsor and executive team immediately','Say nothing to the team to avoid further discouraging them'], correct:1, explanation:'The sequence matters: acknowledgment first, then action. Skipping acknowledgment and going straight to "here\'s the recovery plan" doesn\'t allow the team to process what happened, may feel like blame dismissal, and misses the root cause insight needed to prevent recurrence. Acknowledgment (validating the difficulty, avoiding blame, expressing confidence) is psychological first aid that maintains trust. Retrospective identifies root causes (what caused the miss?). Co-creating the recovery plan generates team ownership. This sequence is consistent with Psychological Safety research — teams that can talk about failures recover faster than teams where failure is shameful.' },
  { domain:'People', scenario:'A project manager is managing a team member who consistently delivers high-quality technical work but refuses to share knowledge with colleagues, creating a team dependency and single point of failure risk.', question:'What should the PM do?', options:['Accept the behavior since the quality of work is high','Have a private conversation explaining that knowledge hoarding (whether intentional or habitual) creates project risk and limits the team\'s capability. Frame knowledge sharing as a professional development opportunity (mentoring, tech talks, documentation) and include it as an explicit performance expectation. If needed, restructure work to require pair programming.','Threaten performance consequences if knowledge is not shared','Accept the risk and document it in the risk register without addressing the behavior'], correct:1, explanation:'Knowledge hoarding — intentional or not — is a team and organizational risk that the PM must address directly. Approach: frame as professional growth ("your expertise is valuable — teaching it multiplies your impact"), create structural knowledge-sharing mechanisms (pair programming, tech talks, architecture documentation standards), and include knowledge transfer as a team norm in the Team Charter. If the behavior is intentional ("I\'ll keep this knowledge to keep my job"), that\'s a trust and culture issue that requires direct conversation about the professional standard of collaborative team membership. The risk register documents the risk but doesn\'t resolve the behavior.' },
  { domain:'People', scenario:'A project team is newly formed. During the first sprint planning, the team experiences significant conflict over technical approach, roles, and priorities. The PM is concerned about delivery.', question:'What does this suggest about the team\'s stage of development?', options:['The team is dysfunctional and should be reorganized','This is normal Storming (Tuckman model) behavior — individuals are establishing their positions, testing boundaries, and asserting their views. The PM\'s role is to facilitate: establish clear roles, create shared norms, facilitate issue resolution, and help the team reach Norming (shared understanding) as quickly as possible.','The team needs stronger directive leadership to establish order','The conflict indicates fundamental incompatibility — the PM should replace conflicting members'], correct:1, explanation:'Tuckman\'s model: Forming (polite, unclear roles) → Storming (conflict, position assertion) → Norming (shared norms, collaboration) → Performing (high performance) → Adjourning. First-sprint conflict is typical Storming — not dysfunction, but a development stage to be managed. The PM\'s role during Storming: facilitate (not avoid or suppress) conflict, establish clear decision-making protocols, co-create team norms, and help the team find their first collaborative wins to build trust. Strong directive leadership (option C) in Storming can be appropriate for decisions, but the PM should be coaching toward self-management, not creating permanent dependency.' },
  { domain:'People', scenario:'A project manager\'s team has achieved high performance. A new stakeholder is added to the project with authority to give the team direct instructions. This disrupts established team dynamics.', question:'What should the project manager do?', options:['Allow the new stakeholder direct access since they have legitimate authority','Proactively manage the integration: brief the new stakeholder on team governance (all instructions go through the PM), introduce them to the team in a structured way, clarify their role and input boundaries, and protect the team\'s established working norms from disruption','Tell the team to simply adjust their working norms to accommodate the new stakeholder','Complain to the sponsor about the new stakeholder being added'], correct:1, explanation:'Protecting a high-performing team\'s dynamics from disruptive external forces is a key PM responsibility. A new stakeholder with direct instruction authority — without established team governance awareness — can restart the Storming phase and damage Performing dynamics. The PM\'s role: proactively educate the new stakeholder on how the team operates, establish clear communication channels (requests to the PM who filters and integrates), and provide the stakeholder with appropriate visibility (sprint reviews, written updates) without unmediated team disruption. This is boundary management — protecting team performance from external noise.' },
  { domain:'People', scenario:'A project manager observes that a team member is struggling with a personal crisis (family illness) that is affecting their work attendance and output. The team member has not disclosed the situation.', question:'What should the PM do?', options:['Issue a performance improvement plan immediately since attendance is below standard','Create a private opportunity for the team member to share what is going on (without prying), offer organizational resources (EAP, flexible schedule, bereavement leave), adjust expectations temporarily if needed, and treat the situation with strict confidentiality','Announce to the team that performance expectations apply equally regardless of personal circumstances','Assign the team member\'s work to others without discussion'], correct:1, explanation:'PMI\'s stewardship principle requires caring for people as whole humans, not just role-fillers. Personal crises affect work — the PM\'s response should be human first. Creating a private opening ("I\'ve noticed you seem to be going through something — if there\'s anything affecting your work that I can help with, I\'m here") allows the team member to disclose at their own comfort. If disclosed: offer resources, adjust temporarily, maintain confidentiality absolutely. If not disclosed: document the performance impact for due process, but continue offering support. Performance improvement plans are appropriate only when all support avenues have been exhausted. This is leading with compassion and professionalism.' },
  { domain:'People', scenario:'A project manager wants to improve team cohesion and shared purpose. The project has a clear technical scope but the PM hasn\'t articulated why the project matters to the organization and society.', question:'What is the MOST effective intervention?', options:['Create a detailed project charter and share it with the team','Articulate a compelling project narrative: connect the technical deliverables to their ultimate human impact ("this system will enable 10,000 nurses to spend more time with patients"), share stakeholder success stories, and make the mission tangible through direct stakeholder interactions (let the team meet the people their work serves)','Implement a team reward program tied to milestone achievement','Increase the frequency of team meetings to build shared identity'], correct:1, explanation:'Purpose — understanding the meaningful impact of one\'s work — is one of the most powerful intrinsic motivators (Daniel Pink\'s Drive framework: Autonomy, Mastery, Purpose). Teams who see the human impact of their work demonstrate higher engagement, discretionary effort, and resilience during difficult periods. The PM\'s role: translate technical scope into human impact narrative, make beneficiaries real (stories, meetings, testimonials), and consistently reinforce WHY this project matters. Technical team members particularly respond to purpose — they want their expertise to matter, not just to build systems. Rewards (option C) address hygiene, not motivation.' },
  { domain:'People', scenario:'An agile coach is working with a team that has adopted Scrum. The team\'s Product Owner is frequently unavailable during sprints, making it difficult for the team to clarify requirements and make decisions.', question:'What should the agile coach/PM do?', options:['Let the team make all product decisions in the PO\'s absence','Escalate the PO availability problem to the PO\'s manager, help the PO understand that their availability is a sprint prerequisite not an optional commitment, explore structural solutions (dedicated PO time blocks, a PO proxy for routine decisions, async response protocols), and consider whether the PO role needs to be more formally supported organizationally','Accept this as a limitation of the organization\'s Scrum adoption','Extend the sprint length to compensate for PO unavailability'], correct:1, explanation:'Product Owner availability is a foundational Scrum requirement — without it, teams make assumptions that lead to rework, miss strategic opportunities, and lose the PO\'s priority judgment that is the core value of the role. The agile coach/PM must escalate this as a systemic risk: "Sprint commitments depend on PO availability for clarification — currently we are making decisions without PO input that should be theirs." Structural solutions (protected PO time, proxy authority for routine decisions, async decision protocols) reduce the friction. If the organizational PO model fundamentally can\'t support Scrum, the approach may need to be adapted. This is systemic impediment removal.' },
  { domain:'People', scenario:'A project manager needs to conduct a performance review for a team member. The review period included a challenging project phase where the team member made a major error but also demonstrated exceptional recovery and growth.', question:'What is the MOST effective approach to the performance review?', options:['Focus only on the error since it had project impact','Provide a balanced, specific, evidence-based assessment: acknowledge the error specifically (what happened, what impact it had), equally acknowledge the recovery and growth demonstrated, set specific expectations for the next period, and discuss development opportunities that build on demonstrated strengths and address the failure pattern','Focus only on the recovery to maintain motivation','Defer the review until a time when the team member has more positive results to discuss'], correct:1, explanation:'Balanced performance feedback is both honest and developmental. A review that only focuses on the error is discouraging and incomplete — it misses the growth opportunity and may overlook genuine progress. A review that only focuses on recovery misses the learning from the error and is dishonest. Specific, evidence-based assessment ("on March 15, this happened and had X impact; following that, you did Y which resulted in Z") is far more actionable than general comments. Looking forward with specific development expectations closes the review with direction, not just judgment. This is PMBOK 6 Develop Team competency in performance management.' },
  { domain:'People', scenario:'A project is transitioning from one project manager to another. The outgoing PM is departing on good terms. The new PM wants to build trust quickly.', question:'What should the new PM do in the first two weeks?', options:['Immediately announce changes to demonstrate leadership and establish their identity','Prioritize listening: meet with each team member individually to understand their experience, concerns, and expertise; review project documentation; meet with stakeholders; identify current issues and risks; and make no significant changes until the context is fully understood. Then share initial observations and planned approach with the team.','Continue exactly what the previous PM was doing to minimize disruption','Ask the previous PM to remain involved to provide continuity'], correct:1, explanation:'Trust in new leadership is built through listening, not immediate action. The "100-day listening tour" principle: new leaders who make changes before understanding context destroy institutional knowledge, invalidate earned team trust, and create unnecessary disruption. The new PM should: meet everyone, review everything, and make NO significant changes in the first 2 weeks. Then: share observations ("here\'s what I\'ve heard and seen"), acknowledge what\'s working, and introduce specific, explained improvements. This approach signals respect for the existing team and builds the relational foundation for effective leadership. It\'s counterintuitively the fastest path to high PM impact.' },
  { domain:'People', scenario:'During a team meeting, two team members have a heated disagreement. The disagreement becomes personal and one team member storms out of the meeting.', question:'What should the project manager do?', options:['Continue the meeting without the team member who left','Pause the meeting, check on the team member who left privately, resume the meeting without the disputed topic, then separately facilitate a mediated conversation between the two involved team members after both have had time to calm down','Use the incident as a teaching moment for the whole team about professional behavior','Discipline both team members for unprofessional behavior in the meeting'], correct:1, explanation:'Escalated conflict in a group setting requires immediate de-escalation and private resolution. Continuing in public while someone is emotionally overwhelmed produces no value and creates audience dynamics that make resolution harder. Check on the person who left (human care), give both time to cool (emotional regulation), resume the meeting on different agenda items to preserve team time, then facilitate mediated resolution privately after emotional temperatures drop. Public "teaching moments" about the incident embarrass both parties and create resentment. Discipline before attempting resolution is disproportionate. Privacy protects relationships and enables genuine resolution.' },
  { domain:'People', scenario:'A project manager is building a high-performing agile team and wants to optimize team composition. The current team has 12 members. The project requires both front-end, back-end, and QA expertise.', question:'What team structure is MOST effective for an agile approach?', options:['One large 12-person team working on all features together','Two or three small cross-functional teams (4-6 members each), each containing front-end, back-end, and QA expertise, working on different product areas simultaneously with coordination at the feature integration level','Three specialty teams (front-end team, back-end team, QA team) working in sequence','One team for development and one team for testing, coordinating through the PM'], correct:1, explanation:'Agile research (based on Amazon\'s two-pizza rule and Scrum guidelines of 3-9 members) shows that small, cross-functional, self-organizing teams outperform large groups. With 12 members, two or three cross-functional teams (3-4 members each with the full stack of skills) can work in parallel on different product areas, producing faster throughput than one large team with coordination overhead. Specialty teams (option C) create waterfall-in-agile — front-end passes to back-end passes to QA — killing agile flow benefits. Separate dev/test teams (option D) recreate the quality handoff problem. Cross-functional team composition is foundational to agile effectiveness.' },
  { domain:'People', scenario:'A team member completes their project tasks well but consistently fails to document their work as required by the team\'s Definition of Done. When reminded, they say: "My code speaks for itself."', question:'What should the project manager do?', options:['Accept the rationale since good code may not need extensive documentation','Have a clear conversation explaining that documentation is a team commitment (part of DoD), not an individual preference — it enables maintenance, onboarding, and team resilience. Set a clear expectation with a specific example of the documentation standard required. If non-compliance continues, address as a behavioral performance issue.','Remove documentation from the DoD to remove the conflict','Report the team member to HR for insubordination'], correct:1, explanation:'DoD commitments are team agreements, not suggestions. "My code speaks for itself" is a common but problematic professional belief — undocumented code is a maintenance liability, onboarding burden, and team risk (bus factor). The PM must: explain the business reasons for documentation (maintenance, knowledge transfer, auditability), show what acceptable documentation looks like (specific example reduces interpretation variance), set a clear behavioral expectation, and monitor. If the team member continues to violate a clear, reasonable team standard, it becomes a performance management issue. Starting with HR escalation is disproportionate — progressive escalation applies.' },

// ─────────────────────────── PROCESS DOMAIN (~90 questions) ───────────────────────────
  { domain:'Process', scenario:'A project manager has completed risk identification and qualitative analysis. The risk register shows 8 risks classified as high-priority. The sponsor asks: "What is the total financial exposure from these 8 risks?"', question:'What tool should the PM use to answer this question?', options:['Multiply each risk\'s probability by its impact and add them together (Expected Monetary Value sum)','Use the Expected Monetary Value (EMV) analysis: for each risk, multiply probability × financial impact, then sum across all risks to calculate the total expected monetary exposure for contingency reserve planning — but note that EMV assumes risks are independent','Create a decision tree with all 8 risks as decision nodes','Ask the team to subjectively estimate total exposure based on experience'], correct:1, explanation:'Expected Monetary Value (EMV) analysis is the standard quantitative technique for this question. EMV per risk = P × I. Total EMV = Σ(EMV per risk). This provides the basis for contingency reserve calculation. Critical caveat: EMV assumes risk independence — if risks are correlated (one risk triggers another), simple EMV summation understates true exposure. Decision tree analysis (option C) is appropriate when risks have sequential decisions and outcomes. Monte Carlo simulation handles correlations and distributions better than simple EMV for complex portfolios. For 8 independent risks, EMV sum is the appropriate and efficient answer.' },
  { domain:'Process', scenario:'A project schedule shows four sequential activities: Design (8d), Development (15d), Testing (10d), Deployment (3d). The project manager wants to identify opportunities to compress the schedule without adding resources.', question:'Which compression technique is available, and to which activities does it apply?', options:['Crashing all four activities by adding resources','Fast-tracking: overlap Development and Testing (begin testing completed modules while development continues on others) since Development and Testing have partial sequential logic that can be parallelized','Crash Testing by running multiple test cycles simultaneously','Fast-tracking Design and Deployment since they are both short activities'], correct:1, explanation:'Fast-tracking requires identifying activities that can logically overlap — where earlier activities can be partially complete before later activities begin. Development and Testing have natural fast-track potential: as development modules are completed, testing can begin on those modules while development continues on others (incremental testing). Design must be substantially complete before development starts (less fast-track opportunity). Deployment logically follows completed testing. Crashing adds resources (different technique). Fast-tracking Design and Deployment makes no sense — they are boundary activities with limited parallelism opportunity. The development-testing overlap is the classic software schedule fast-tracking answer.' },
  { domain:'Process', scenario:'A project team is planning for a major software release. The testing plan includes unit tests (developer-created), integration tests, system tests, and user acceptance tests (UAT). The client is responsible for UAT.', question:'In what sequence should these testing types be conducted and why?', options:['UAT first to ensure client requirements are met before internal testing','Unit Tests → Integration Tests → System Tests → UAT. Each level validates incrementally broader scope, and defects found earlier are cheaper to fix. UAT by definition validates against user needs — it requires the system to be technically complete and internally validated first.','System Tests first to identify critical defects early','All test types can be conducted simultaneously to save time'], correct:1, explanation:'Test sequence follows a logical quality assurance principle: validate component-level correctness (unit tests) before integration-level behavior (integration tests) before system-wide behavior (system tests) before user-perspective validation (UAT). Each level builds on the previous: you cannot meaningfully validate system behavior if components don\'t work individually. UAT is the most expensive to fix defects found at — it requires a technically stable system. Finding a unit-level defect during UAT costs 10-100× more than finding it during unit testing. This is the Cost of Quality principle applied to test sequencing.' },
  { domain:'Process', scenario:'A project manager is controlling scope for a software project. The project team received verbal instructions from a senior executive to add a major new feature. The feature was not in the scope baseline.', question:'What must the project manager do?', options:['Implement the feature since an executive has more authority than the PM','Respectfully explain to the executive that all scope changes — regardless of requester authority — must follow the Integrated Change Control process. Document the verbal request, submit a formal change request, assess impact, and obtain CCB approval before any work begins.','Implement the feature and inform the sponsor after the fact','Refuse the request and tell the executive to formally submit it themselves'], correct:1, explanation:'The Change Control process applies universally — authority does not exempt anyone from governance. The PM\'s role is to enable the process, not enforce hierarchy in either direction. The professional response: acknowledge the executive\'s input respectfully, explain the process briefly (impact on baseline, CCB approval requirement), offer to facilitate the change request submission, and never begin work on unapproved changes. This protects the executive (by ensuring impact is understood), protects the project (by maintaining baseline integrity), and protects the PM (by maintaining governance accountability). PMI Principle: governance applies to all change, regardless of source.' },
  { domain:'Process', scenario:'A project manager is reviewing a status report that shows Project X has a CPI of 1.2 and SPI of 0.85. The project is 65% complete.', question:'What does this mean and what questions should the PM investigate?', options:['The project is performing well — no action needed','CPI = 1.2 (under budget — getting $1.20 of value per $1 spent) but SPI = 0.85 (behind schedule — only 85% of planned work completed). Investigate: What is causing the schedule delay? Is it resource availability, dependency issues, or scope discovery? Can the cost savings be reallocated to compress the schedule? Is the project\'s end date at risk?','The project is behind schedule and over budget','The CPI and SPI cancel each other out — the project is on track overall'], correct:1, explanation:'CPI > 1.0 = under budget (positive). SPI < 1.0 = behind schedule (negative). This is a common scenario worth investigating: why is the team spending less than planned but progressing slower? Possible causes: resource gaps (people not available = less spending, but also less work done); underestimated work complexity (doing less with the budget available); or scope reduction (less work in progress). The cost savings could potentially fund schedule acceleration (crashing) — but only if the root cause of schedule delay is resource-related. This is the nuanced EVM reading that differentiates PMP-ready candidates from those who memorize formulas only.' },
  { domain:'Process', scenario:'A project manager is creating the Work Breakdown Structure for a new hospital construction project. A team member suggests that the WBS should be organized by construction phase (Foundation, Structure, Exterior, Interior, Systems). Another team member suggests organizing by building zone (West Wing, East Wing, Lobby, Basement).', question:'Which WBS organization approach is correct?', options:['Phase-based WBS is always the PMBOK-recommended approach','Both can be valid — the WBS organization should reflect the most useful way to manage, estimate, and control the work for this specific project. A phase-based WBS naturally aligns with the construction sequence; a zone-based WBS may align better with contractor responsibilities and parallel workstreams.','A zone-based WBS is preferred because it enables parallel work','The WBS must be organized by Knowledge Area to align with PMBOK structure'], correct:1, explanation:'PMBOK does not prescribe a single WBS organization structure. WBS can be organized by: phase/process group, deliverable/product component, geographic zone/location, contractor/organizational unit, or any combination that best supports project control. For construction, phase-based WBS naturally reflects construction sequencing (nothing happens before foundation). Zone-based WBS works when different teams work on different areas simultaneously. The choice should be driven by: how work is contracted, how progress will be measured, and what structure best enables monitoring and control. This is a tailoring decision — PMBOK 7 Principle #7.' },
  { domain:'Process', scenario:'An agile project team has been working for 6 months. The Product Owner introduces 40 new user stories from a major stakeholder group that was not involved in the initial backlog creation.', question:'What should happen?', options:['Implement all 40 stories in the next sprint to address the backlog gap','The PO should review the 40 stories, assess their value and priority relative to existing backlog items, integrate them into the product backlog in priority order, refine them to meet the definition of ready, and schedule them for future sprints based on velocity and priorities — this is normal backlog evolution','Reject the new stories since they weren\'t planned at project start','Add all 40 stories to the next sprint without prioritization to show responsiveness'], correct:1, explanation:'Product Backlog is a living document — new stories from newly engaged stakeholders are expected and normal in agile. The PO\'s role: evaluate the stories (some may be duplicates, some may be trivial, some may be critical), prioritize them relative to existing items (value, dependencies, strategic alignment), refine them to DoR standards (accepted criteria, estimable), and schedule based on velocity. The sprint team doesn\'t implement all 40 at once — that ignores capacity and priority. This is adaptive backlog management — a core agile process competency.' },
  { domain:'Process', scenario:'During project execution, the PM receives an issue log update showing 15 open issues, 8 of which have been open for more than 30 days without resolution. The issue log shows these 8 issues are assigned to various team members.', question:'What should the project manager do?', options:['Archive the old issues since they are likely no longer relevant','Review each unresolved issue with its owner: identify what is blocking resolution, determine if escalation is needed, set firm resolution dates, and for issues that cannot be resolved at the team level, escalate through appropriate channels. Update the issue log with current status and next actions.','Remove issues from the log to reduce management overhead','Reassign all 8 issues to the most senior team member available'], correct:1, explanation:'Issues left unresolved for 30+ days signal either: the issue owner doesn\'t have authority/resources to resolve it (needs escalation), the issue has low actual priority (should be closed or deprioritized formally), or issue management is not being enforced. The PM\'s role: triage each issue — blocked by authority/resource (escalate), low priority (close or defer formally), team member inaction (coach + set deadline). The issue log is a project management tool, not a parking lot. Issues that remain unresolved too long become organizational risks. Regular issue review cadence (weekly, not monthly) prevents backlog accumulation.' },
  { domain:'Process', scenario:'A project team using SAFe is preparing for their first PI Planning event. The program has 6 teams and will plan for 10 sprints (5 iterations × 2 weeks each).', question:'What are the PRIMARY deliverables of a PI Planning event?', options:['Detailed task assignments for each team member for the next 10 sprints','PI Objectives (committed and stretch goals) for each team, a Program Board showing cross-team dependencies and milestones, identified risks (ROAMed), and a high-level iteration plan for each team — with team velocity-based capacity planning','A fixed Gantt chart for the entire PI period','A vendor list for the PI period'], correct:1, explanation:'SAFe PI Planning outputs (aligned with exam content): (1) Team PI Objectives: committed (high confidence) and stretch (aspirational) goals that teams own for the PI. (2) Program Board: visual display of cross-team dependencies, milestones, and important dates — enables dependency management and coordination. (3) ROAM risks: Resolved, Owned, Accepted, Mitigated — systematic risk disposition during planning. (4) Team Iteration Plans: high-level allocation of work to iterations with capacity-based commitments. The key distinguishing element is Program Board and team PI Objectives — these differentiate PI Planning output from regular sprint planning output.' },
  { domain:'Process', scenario:'A project manager is analyzing lessons learned from 5 previous projects of the same type. Common themes show that scope creep occurred in all 5 projects during the Executing phase, typically around the 60-70% completion mark.', question:'What proactive measures should be built into the current project to prevent this pattern?', options:['Add scope creep to the risk register and monitor it','Implement multiple preventive controls: ensure all stakeholders have signed scope baseline documentation, implement formal change control with documented decision criteria for scope requests, schedule specific "scope stability reviews" at the 50% and 70% completion marks, and brief the sponsor on the historical pattern with a request for active scope governance support.','Simply enforce the change control process as currently designed','Document the historical pattern and address scope creep if it occurs'], correct:1, explanation:'Historical lessons learned are some of the most valuable risk inputs available. A pattern across 5 projects is not coincidence — it indicates a systemic vulnerability in the project type at a predictable point. Proactive measures: documentation of scope agreement, formal change control education for all stakeholders at kickoff, scheduled scope stability reviews at the identified risk window (60-70%), sponsor engagement as a sponsor change control champion. This is lessons-learned-driven risk prevention — one of the highest-ROI applications of OPAs. Simply monitoring (option A) is reactive; building preventive controls is proactive.' },
  { domain:'Process', scenario:'A project manager is planning a project with the following activity network. Activity A(4d) must finish before B(6d) starts. B must finish before C(5d) starts. Activity D(8d) can start after A starts (with a 2-day lag). D must finish before C starts.', question:'What is the critical path?', options:['A → B → C = 15 days','A → D → C: A(4d) + D(8d) + C(5d) = 17 days is the critical path since it is longer than A → B → C = 4 + 6 + 5 = 15 days','B → C = 11 days','Cannot determine without more information'], correct:1, explanation:'Path analysis: Path 1: A → B → C = 4 + 6 + 5 = 15 days. Path 2: A → D → C: D starts after A starts with 2-day lag, so D effective start = day 2. D(8d) finishes at day 10. A finishes at day 4. The controlling predecessor for C is whichever finishes last: B finishes at day 4 + 6 = day 10. D finishes at day 2 + 8 = day 10. Both finish at day 10! C then takes 5 days: project duration = 15 days. Actually, both paths are equal at 15 days — making them BOTH critical paths with zero float. The project has a multiple critical path scenario, which is a high-risk schedule situation.' },
  { domain:'Process', scenario:'A project manager is monitoring a construction project. The project schedule shows that material deliveries are on the critical path. The PM receives notification that a critical material shipment will be delayed by 3 weeks due to port congestion.', question:'What is the FIRST thing the project manager should do?', options:['Issue a change request to extend the project deadline by 3 weeks','Perform an immediate impact analysis: which activities are dependent on this material? Is there a near-critical path that might become the new critical path? What recovery options exist? (alternative suppliers, air freight, sequencing changes to use available materials first). Then communicate options with trade-offs to the sponsor.','Order the materials from an alternative supplier immediately without impact analysis','Update the risk register and wait for the shipment'], correct:1, explanation:'A 3-week delay on a critical path material is a significant project event requiring immediate multi-step response. Impact analysis first: which activities are affected? Can any non-material-dependent work be brought forward? Are there near-critical paths that now become critical? Then recovery options: alternative supplier (cost?), expedited shipping (cost vs. delay value?), redesign to use available materials (scope change?). Only after understanding impact and options can the PM present a recommendation. Issuing a change request for 3-week extension before exploring recovery is premature. Waiting passively wastes critical response time.' },
  { domain:'Process', scenario:'A project manager discovers that the project\'s control account manager has been approving work in excess of the authorized Control Account budget without submitting change requests.', question:'What must the PM do?', options:['Retroactively approve the overspending since the work has been done','Stop any further unauthorized work, document the specific overages, require the control account manager to submit change requests for all overages, review the control account manager\'s understanding of their authority level, and establish clearer authorization limits and enforcement protocols going forward','Accept it as a minor governance deviation and document it','Ask the project sponsor to retroactively expand all control account budgets to cover the overages'], correct:1, explanation:'Unauthorized cost overruns are a governance and accountability failure. The PM must: immediately stop further unauthorized work (an ongoing overrun is an escalating risk), document what was approved vs. what was spent, require retroactive change requests for overruns (so the CCB can make informed decisions), address the control account manager\'s behavior directly (was it a misunderstanding of authority or intentional circumvention?), and strengthen authorization controls. Retroactive approval without CCB review violates governance. Sponsor blanket expansion is also governance bypass. This is cost control and change management enforcement.' },
  { domain:'Process', scenario:'An agile team is using a Definition of Ready (DoR) to screen user stories before they enter a sprint. A team member argues that the DoR creates too much planning overhead and should be eliminated.', question:'What is the purpose of the DoR and when is it appropriate?', options:['DoR is a bureaucratic artifact that slows agile delivery and should be removed','DoR ensures that stories are sufficiently understood and refined before sprint commitment, preventing mid-sprint ambiguity, rework, and incomplete work at sprint end. It is appropriate when: stories are frequently discovered to be unclear during sprints, causing significant rework. The DoR content should be calibrated to what\'s actually needed, not maximally prescriptive.','DoR replaces the need for sprint planning','DoR is mandatory in all agile frameworks and cannot be modified'], correct:1, explanation:'The Definition of Ready is a team agreement (not a Scrum requirement — it\'s an agile best practice) that specifies minimum criteria for a story to be sprint-ready: understood by the team, estimable, testable, small enough to complete in a sprint. Its purpose is waste reduction: stories that enter sprints without DoR compliance frequently stall, require mid-sprint clarification, or spill over — all of which reduce throughput and quality. If a team rarely encounters mid-sprint ambiguity, the DoR may be lightweight or unnecessary. If they frequently do, DoR prevents that waste. The calibration principle: just enough criteria to prevent the documented problems, not maximum bureaucracy.' },
  { domain:'Process', scenario:'A project manager needs to create the Project Management Plan for a 24-month project with a $15M budget. The sponsor asks how detailed the initial plan should be.', question:'What is the appropriate level of planning detail?', options:['Plan everything in full detail for all 24 months before starting execution','Use progressive elaboration and rolling wave planning: plan the first 3-4 months in sufficient detail for reliable execution, plan subsequent phases at milestone/phase level, and elaborate detail as the project approaches each phase. A 24-month fully-detailed upfront plan is unreliable at month 24 level.','Plan only the first sprint/phase — a 24-month plan is impossible to create upfront','Create the maximum level of detail possible to minimize execution risk'], correct:1, explanation:'The Cone of Uncertainty principle: predictability decreases as planning horizon increases. A 24-month, full-detail upfront plan is expensive to create and unreliable at the far horizon — activities, resources, and requirements will change before month 24 begins. Rolling Wave Planning (PMBOK Section 6.3) provides detail where it enables reliable execution (near term) and maintains strategic direction at milestone level for future phases. The $15M budget requires proper governance documentation at phase level. This balances the legitimate need for fiscal control with the reality of planning uncertainty. This is one of the most practically important project management principles.' },
  { domain:'Process', scenario:'A project team is estimating costs using bottom-up estimating. The work breakdown structure has 180 work packages. The team lead suggests that estimating each work package individually will take 3 weeks of team time.', question:'What is the trade-off the project manager must consider?', options:['Bottom-up estimating is always required regardless of time investment','The 3-week effort for higher-accuracy estimates must be weighed against the value of that accuracy: if the project is $5M, a 5% accuracy improvement could prevent $250K of overruns — easily worth 3 weeks. If the project is $200K, 3 weeks of estimation is disproportionate. The PM must decide if the accuracy improvement justifies the investment.','Always use analogous estimating to save time','Bottom-up estimation should be delegated to reduce the 3-week estimate'], correct:1, explanation:'Estimation is an investment decision. Bottom-up provides highest accuracy (−5% to +10%) but requires significant effort. The cost-benefit: what is the value of improved accuracy vs. the cost of the estimation process? For a large, complex project with significant financial consequences of overruns, 3 weeks is often justified. For a smaller project, analogous or parametric may be sufficient. The PM must make an explicit, documented decision about estimation approach based on project size, risk, and the cost of inaccuracy — not reflexively apply one technique to all situations. This is tailoring applied to planning processes.' },
  { domain:'Process', scenario:'A project manager is tracking benefits realization for a completed ERP implementation. Six months post-implementation, the promised efficiency gains are not materializing.', question:'What should the project manager/benefits owner do?', options:['Close the benefits realization tracking since the project is technically complete','Investigate root causes for non-realization: Are users actually using the new system features? Were training and change management adequate? Are process changes that the efficiency depends on being implemented by management? Identify corrective actions at the process/behavioral level and track them formally.','Report the benefit shortfall to executive management and close tracking','Assume benefits will emerge with more time and continue monthly measurement without intervention'], correct:1, explanation:'Benefits don\'t realize automatically from system delivery — they require behavior change, process adoption, and management reinforcement. When benefits are not materializing 6 months post-implementation, root cause investigation is essential: low user adoption (training gap?), managers not enforcing new processes (change management gap?), technical issues preventing feature use (implementation gap?)? Each cause has a different corrective action. Simply reporting and closing (option C) abandons the organizational value commitment. Waiting longer without investigation (option D) delays corrective action when intervention is still effective. This is the final stage of the project management value chain: benefits realization management.' },
  { domain:'Process', scenario:'A project manager is planning a major software deployment that will affect 5000 end users. The deployment must occur with zero downtime. The PM is reviewing the deployment approach with the technical team.', question:'What risk management strategy is MOST appropriate for zero-downtime requirements?', options:['Accept the risk of downtime since zero-downtime is technically very difficult','Design a deployment architecture specifically to eliminate the risk: blue-green deployment (maintain two identical environments, switch traffic instantly), canary releases (roll out to 1% of users first, monitor, then expand), automated rollback triggers, and parallel run period. Zero-downtime is a hard requirement that must be designed into the solution, not accepted as impossible.','Transfer the risk to the vendor by including a zero-downtime SLA in the contract','Perform a dry run and accept whatever downtime it produces'], correct:1, explanation:'When a risk is a hard requirement violation (zero downtime = business/contractual requirement), the response cannot be acceptance or simple transfer. It requires risk avoidance through architectural design: blue-green deployments (two identical production environments — switch traffic between them with no user impact), feature flags (enable features for subsets of users), canary releases (gradual rollout with automated health checks), and automated rollback (instant revert if error rates spike). These are industry-standard practices for high-availability deployments. The PM must ensure the technical architecture specifically addresses this requirement. SLA transfer (option C) still means downtime occurs — the vendor just pays for it.' },
  { domain:'Process', scenario:'An agile team has been working for 12 months and velocity has been stable at 45 story points/sprint. There are 180 story points remaining in the product backlog. The Product Owner asks for a release forecast.', question:'What is the forecast and what confidence level can be stated?', options:['Exactly 4 sprints remaining (180/45 = 4.0)','Based on 12 months of stable velocity at 45 points/sprint, the forecast is approximately 4 sprints (180/45 = 4.0). However, velocity varies sprint to sprint. Using velocity standard deviation from historical data would produce a confidence range (e.g., 85% confidence of completion in 3-5 sprints). Also note: if the backlog is likely to grow (common in agile), the actual completion may be later.','Cannot forecast in agile since scope is always changing','10 sprints since agile projects always take longer than planned'], correct:1, explanation:'Agile forecasting using velocity: 180 points ÷ 45 points/sprint = 4 sprints as the expected value. Professional communication includes uncertainty: single-point estimates imply false precision. Using historical velocity variance produces a confidence interval ("85% probability of completion in 3-5 sprints"). The PO should also be informed that product backlog growth (new stories added, requirements discovered) is common and may extend the forecast. This is honest, data-based probabilistic forecasting — the professional agile alternative to false Gantt chart precision. The PMP exam increasingly tests this nuanced agile forecasting competency.' },
  { domain:'Process', scenario:'A project manager is planning the stakeholder engagement for a controversial project that will consolidate two competing business units. Known hostile stakeholders include unit heads from both departments.', question:'What engagement strategy should the PM develop for these hostile stakeholders?', options:['Exclude hostile stakeholders from project communications to prevent sabotage','Design a high-engagement strategy for hostile stakeholders: frequent bilateral meetings, early involvement in decisions that affect them, transparency about how their concerns are being addressed, co-creation of solutions where possible, and senior sponsor involvement in stakeholder bridging. Monitor engagement level changes regularly.','Communicate only through formal written reports to hostile stakeholders','Let the executive sponsor manage all hostile stakeholder relationships'], correct:1, explanation:'The stakeholder engagement assessment matrix identifies stakeholders by current state (resistant, neutral, supportive) and desired state (typically at least neutral). For hostile stakeholders in a controversial project: high engagement (not avoidance) is the professional strategy. Early involvement in decisions that affect them reduces surprise and resentment. Bilateral meetings allow their concerns to be heard and addressed privately before they become public obstruction. Senior sponsor involvement signals organizational commitment. Monitoring engagement changes tracks whether the strategy is working. Excluding hostile stakeholders guarantees they remain hostile and become obstructors.' },
  { domain:'Process', scenario:'A project is using time-and-materials contracts for software development services. After 6 months, the PM reviews the contract spend and realizes costs are 40% over the original estimate.', question:'What should the PM do and what risk does this expose?', options:['Continue since T&M contracts don\'t have cost ceilings','This exposes the key T&M risk: buyer bears all cost risk in an uncapped T&M contract. The PM must immediately: review work orders against delivered value, assess whether the remaining estimate is realistic, consider adding a "not to exceed" cap for remaining work, validate deliverables against expectations, and communicate the overrun and updated forecast to the sponsor. Future T&M contracts should include cost caps.','Terminate the contract since it is over budget','Reduce the scope of remaining work to compensate for the overrun'], correct:1, explanation:'T&M contracts are the most risky for buyers precisely because cost is open-ended. A 40% cost overrun after 6 months signals: original estimates were wrong, scope grew uncontrolled, or vendor efficiency was lower than expected. The PM\'s obligations: validate that delivered value justifies spend, assess remaining work with a realistic estimate, add protective contract provisions (NTE cap for remaining work), and communicate honestly to the sponsor. The risk this exposes (buyer bears all cost risk in T&M) is a core procurement knowledge area topic. Adding NTE caps converts open T&M to bounded T&M — industry standard for longer engagements.' },
  { domain:'Process', scenario:'A project manager receives the monthly EVM report. It shows: BAC = $800K, EV = $480K, AC = $520K, PV = $560K. The project is exactly 60% through its planned duration.', question:'Calculate CPI, SPI, and EAC (assuming current variance is typical).', options:['CPI = 0.923, SPI = 0.857, EAC = $867K','CPI = EV/AC = 480/520 = 0.923 (over budget). SPI = EV/PV = 480/560 = 0.857 (behind schedule). EAC = BAC/CPI = 800/0.923 = $867K (forecast overrun of $67K). CV = -$40K (over budget). SV = -$80K (behind schedule). Project is both over budget and behind schedule.','CPI = 1.08, SPI = 1.17, EAC = $741K','CPI = 0.857, SPI = 0.923, EAC = $933K'], correct:1, explanation:'Step-by-step: CPI = EV/AC = $480K/$520K = 0.923 (over budget — getting only $0.92 per $1 spent). SPI = EV/PV = $480K/$560K = 0.857 (behind schedule — only 85.7% of planned work done). EAC = BAC/CPI = $800K/0.923 = $867K (forecast completion cost). CV = EV−AC = $480K−$520K = −$40K (negative = over budget). SV = EV−PV = $480K−$560K = −$80K (negative = behind schedule). VAC = BAC−EAC = $800K−$867K = −$67K (expected overrun). This calculation demonstrates all core EVM formulas in one scenario — a very common PMP exam question type.' },
  { domain:'Process', scenario:'During planning, the project manager creates a stakeholder engagement assessment matrix. The matrix shows that the project sponsor is currently "unaware" of the project\'s strategic implications.', question:'What should the PM do?', options:['Leave the sponsor in the unaware state since they authorized the project','This is a significant gap — a sponsor who is unaware of strategic implications cannot fulfill their governance and support role effectively. The PM should schedule a strategic briefing for the sponsor to ensure they understand: how the project connects to organizational strategy, what strategic risks exist, what decisions they will need to make, and how their support is critical to stakeholder management.','Change the matrix classification to supportive since the sponsor authorized the project','Only involve the sponsor in routine status reporting since they are busy'], correct:1, explanation:'Stakeholder engagement assessment distinguishes between different knowledge/engagement states: Unaware, Resistant, Neutral, Supportive, Leading. A sponsor who authorized a project but is unaware of its strategic implications may have approved it administratively without understanding the full strategic context — common in large organizations. The PM has an obligation to move the sponsor to at minimum "Supportive" and ideally "Leading" status. Strategic briefing content: project-to-strategy connection, key risks requiring sponsor judgment, governance decisions that will come to them, stakeholder landscape requiring sponsor relationship management. A fully engaged sponsor is a project multiplier.' },
  { domain:'Process', scenario:'A project team identifies a technical risk: "The selected third-party API may be deprecated within the project timeline." The probability is 30% and impact is high (would require redesign of 3 key modules).', question:'What is the MOST appropriate risk response strategy?', options:['Accept the risk since 30% probability is relatively low','Develop a contingency plan: if deprecation is announced, activate pre-designed workaround (abstract the API integration layer now, making API swap feasible). Additionally, monitor the vendor\'s API deprecation announcements and maintain a pre-evaluated alternative API list. This is a risk trigger-based contingency approach.','Avoid the risk by redesigning to eliminate API dependency immediately','Transfer the risk to the third-party vendor through SLA terms'], correct:1, explanation:'This risk has a clever optimal response. At 30% probability with high impact: (1) Monitoring: track vendor API announcements (early warning). (2) Mitigation through architecture: abstract the API integration (design so the API can be swapped without redesigning the 3 modules — reduce impact). (3) Contingency Plan: pre-identify and partially evaluate alternative APIs so if deprecation is announced, response is fast. This combination reduces both probability (monitoring enables early response), reduces impact (architectural abstraction), and pre-positions for fast response if the risk fires. Transfer through SLA doesn\'t help if the vendor simply discontinues the API — there\'s nothing to enforce.' },

// ─────────────────────────── BUSINESS ENVIRONMENT (~14 questions) ───────────────────────────
  { domain:'Business Environment', scenario:'A project manager is asked to lead a new product development project for an overseas market. The PM has no prior experience in that market and has limited budget for market research.', question:'What should the PM do to ensure the project addresses actual market needs?', options:['Apply domestic market assumptions to the overseas market to save research costs','Allocate a portion of the project budget to validate key market assumptions early (customer interviews, small pilot studies, consultation with local distributors or partners) — treating market assumptions as hypotheses to be tested, not facts to be executed. Build iterative market validation into the project approach.','Request additional budget for comprehensive market research before starting','Launch the product and adjust based on market feedback post-release'], correct:1, explanation:'Market assumption validation is a risk management investment. Domestic-to-international market assumptions are notoriously unreliable — consumer preferences, regulatory environments, distribution models, and competitive dynamics differ. With limited budget: prioritize testing the highest-risk assumptions (are customers willing to pay for this? at what price point? through which channels?). Iterative validation (small experiments, early feedback loops) is far more cost-effective than comprehensive pre-research OR post-launch pivot. This is Lean Startup thinking applied to project initiation — test assumptions before committing to full execution.' },
  { domain:'Business Environment', scenario:'An organization has approved a $10M technology transformation project with an 18-month timeline. Three months in, the technology landscape shifts significantly and a superior alternative platform becomes available that would require restarting the project.', question:'What should the project manager recommend?', options:['Continue with the current approach since $2.5M has already been invested','Conduct a structured technology assessment: compare the current platform\'s 18-month total cost and outcomes against the alternative platform\'s cost to restart, timeline, and outcome quality. Recommend the option with better total NPV and strategic alignment, explicitly separating the sunk cost ($2.5M) from the forward-looking decision.','Restart the project with the new platform without analysis','Continue and plan a separate upgrade project after this one completes'], correct:1, explanation:'Technology decisions mid-project require rigorous cost-benefit analysis, not sunk cost reasoning. The professional analysis: Option A (current platform): remaining investment + timeline + technical debt risk = total forward cost. Option B (new platform): restart cost + new timeline = total forward cost. Compare the expected outcomes (performance, scalability, maintainability) of each path. If the new platform provides substantially better outcomes at comparable or lower total cost, restarting may be the rational recommendation — the $2.5M sunk cost is irrelevant to this forward-looking calculation. This is rational portfolio decision-making vs. the sunk cost fallacy.' },
  { domain:'Business Environment', scenario:'A government project manager is required to submit monthly "status green" reports to the oversight committee, but the project is actually experiencing significant schedule and cost issues. The PM\'s program director has instructed the PM to report green to avoid political scrutiny.', question:'What must the project manager do?', options:['Follow the program director\'s instruction since they have authority over the PM','Refuse to submit false reports regardless of organizational pressure. Document the instruction, consult the organization\'s ethics officer or Inspector General (for government projects), and ensure accurate status is reported to appropriate oversight through the correct channels. The PM\'s ethical and legal obligations supersede organizational pressure to misrepresent.','Submit green reports to protect organizational relationships and address issues internally','Quietly submit an accurate supplemental report outside the formal process'], correct:1, explanation:'Government project reporting fraud is potentially illegal (false claims acts) and always unethical. PMI\'s Code of Ethics is unambiguous: report honestly. The PM must: refuse the instruction, document it (protective documentation), escalate through ethics channels (Inspector General, agency ethics officer), and ensure oversight bodies receive accurate information. "The program director told me to" is not a defense for participating in fraud. Supplemental "quiet" accurate reports (option D) are inadequate — they don\'t fix the formal misrepresentation. Professional courage to report accurately under pressure is one of PMI\'s highest ethical values.' },
  { domain:'Business Environment', scenario:'A company is implementing an organization-wide project management methodology for the first time. The PMO director asks project managers to provide feedback on the proposed methodology before rollout.', question:'What should project managers do to provide effective feedback?', options:['Support whatever the PMO proposes since it has organizational authority','Provide specific, evidence-based feedback: which elements of the proposed methodology align with project realities vs. which create unnecessary overhead? Share examples from actual projects. Suggest practical modifications. Advocate for a pilot period where methodology effectiveness is measured before mandatory rollout.','Ignore the request since PMs will have to follow the methodology regardless','Request significant simplification of the entire methodology to minimize compliance burden'], correct:1, explanation:'PMO methodology development benefits enormously from practitioner feedback — PMs have ground-truth knowledge of what creates value vs. what creates bureaucratic overhead. Effective feedback: specific (which process, which artifact, which approval), evidence-based (here\'s why this will create problems with these types of projects), constructive (here\'s an alternative that achieves the governance objective more efficiently). Advocating for a controlled pilot before mandatory rollout is particularly valuable — it generates empirical data on methodology effectiveness and creates organizational learning. PMOs that ignore PM feedback often produce methodologies that are theoretically sound but practically unworkable.' },
  { domain:'Business Environment', scenario:'A project manager is planning a digital health application. During risk planning, the team identifies that the project will collect and process sensitive personal health data from 50,000 users.', question:'What must the project manager include in the project plan to address data governance?', options:['Data governance is the IT department\'s responsibility — the PM focuses on feature delivery','Include explicit data governance deliverables: data classification and handling policies, privacy impact assessment (PIA), regulatory compliance verification (HIPAA in US, GDPR in Europe), data minimization design, user consent mechanisms, breach notification protocol, and security architecture review. These are project scope items, not IT add-ons.','Address data governance only if required by contract','Include a data governance review as a post-implementation activity'], correct:1, explanation:'For projects handling sensitive personal data, privacy and security are not optional governance activities — they are core project deliverables with regulatory, legal, and ethical implications. HIPAA (US health data) and GDPR (EU personal data) impose specific technical and process requirements that must be designed-in from the beginning, not added post-implementation. Privacy by Design means building privacy protections into architecture from the start. The PM must treat data governance as explicit WBS items with associated budget and schedule — not as IT department concerns or post-implementation audits. Discovering compliance gaps at deployment is exponentially more expensive than designing them in.' },
  { domain:'Business Environment', scenario:'An organization is adopting agile practices across all projects. A PM managing a regulatory compliance project (with legally mandated documentation and approval workflows) is told to fully adopt agile.', question:'What should the project manager do?', options:['Adopt full agile methodology since the organization has mandated it','Evaluate which agile practices enhance delivery effectiveness vs. which conflict with regulatory requirements. Adopt compatible practices (iterative development, retrospectives, collaborative planning) while maintaining required regulatory artifacts, documentation standards, and approval workflows. Brief the PMO on the regulatory constraints that limit full agile adoption.','Ignore the organizational mandate and continue with the current approach','Request an exemption from all agile requirements for all regulated projects'], correct:1, explanation:'Regulatory compliance projects operate under external constraints (laws, regulations, audit requirements) that cannot be waived for internal organizational preferences. However, many agile practices are compatible with regulatory environments: iterative development cycles, retrospectives for process improvement, collaborative planning, and daily standups enhance delivery even in regulated contexts. Practices that conflict: agile\'s "working software over comprehensive documentation" conflicts with regulatory documentation requirements; informal approval processes conflict with documented approval workflows. The PM\'s role: selectively apply compatible agile practices, maintain regulatory requirements, and educate the PMO on the rationale. This is intelligent tailoring, not organizational non-compliance.' },
  { domain:'Business Environment', scenario:'A portfolio manager notices that the organization\'s three most expensive projects have collectively consumed 75% of the IT budget for 3 years but have delivered only 35% of their promised business value.', question:'What should the portfolio manager recommend?', options:['Continue the projects since the investment is already made','Recommend a comprehensive portfolio audit: assess each project\'s strategic alignment, remaining expected value, cost to complete, and probability of delivering remaining promised benefits. Based on this analysis, recommend: (1) Continue highest-value projects with accountability mechanisms, (2) Restructure underperforming projects (scope reduction, timeline extension, leadership change), (3) Terminate projects where remaining investment cannot recover sufficient value.','Immediately terminate all three projects','Increase the budget for all three projects to enable them to deliver their promised value'], correct:1, explanation:'A 3-year pattern of value underdelivery despite major investment is a portfolio governance crisis that demands structured response, not continuation or termination by reflex. The portfolio audit provides the evidence for differentiated decisions: some projects may be close to value inflection points and warrant continuation; others may have fundamental structural problems requiring leadership intervention; some may be genuinely unrecoverable and should be terminated. Each decision is based on forward-looking value, not sunk cost. Increasing budget without accountability (option D) repeats the governance failure. Terminating all three without analysis (option C) may terminate genuinely valuable work.' },
  { domain:'Business Environment', scenario:'During a project review, the steering committee asks the PM: "Is this project still aligned with our strategic objectives?" The PM realizes they have not formally reviewed strategic alignment since project initiation 9 months ago.', question:'What should the PM do?', options:['Confirm alignment verbally since the project scope hasn\'t changed','Acknowledge that a formal strategic alignment review is needed: assess the current project deliverables against the organization\'s current strategic objectives (which may have evolved), identify any gaps, and present findings to the steering committee with a recommendation for any adjustments needed.','Claim alignment without investigating since projects shouldn\'t change mid-execution','Ask the steering committee to define the current strategic objectives first'], correct:1, explanation:'Strategic alignment is not a one-time initiation check — it requires periodic monitoring, especially in fast-moving organizational environments (mergers, leadership changes, market shifts, COVID-type disruptions). A 9-month gap without formal review is an oversight. The PM should: immediately conduct an alignment assessment, compare project deliverables against current strategic direction, identify any gaps (scope elements no longer strategic? missing strategic elements?), and present findings honestly. If misalignment is found, work with the steering committee to make corrections. Strategic realignment mid-project is expensive but less expensive than completing a strategically irrelevant project. This reflects PMBOK 7 Principle #4 (Focus on Value).' },
  { domain:'Business Environment', scenario:'An organization is considering outsourcing a critical project function that was previously done internally. The PM is asked to evaluate the make-or-buy decision.', question:'What factors must the make-or-buy analysis include?', options:['Only the direct cost comparison between internal and external delivery','Comprehensive analysis including: direct cost comparison (internal labor + overhead vs. vendor cost), strategic considerations (does this capability need to remain internal?), quality and performance risk, vendor management overhead, intellectual property and confidentiality risk, long-term dependency risk, transition cost, and reversibility (can we bring it back in-house if needed?).','Only whether internal staff have the required technical skills','Only the vendor\'s past performance ratings'], correct:1, explanation:'Make-or-buy analysis (PMBOK 6 Section 12.1) is far more complex than a cost comparison. Strategic factors: once outsourced, rebuilding the capability may be extremely difficult (skills atrophy, institutional knowledge lost) — is this capability a strategic differentiator? Quality risk: can the vendor match or exceed internal quality standards? IP/confidentiality: what data will the vendor access? Dependency risk: once dependent on this vendor, what is the negotiating position at renewal? Transition cost: changing vendors in the future is expensive. Reversibility: if the decision proves wrong, can it be undone? Only a fully-factored analysis enables an informed make-or-buy recommendation.' },
  { domain:'Business Environment', scenario:'A PM leading an IT project in a financial institution receives a request to implement a feature that would enable automated loan decisions. The institution\'s ethics committee raises concerns about algorithmic bias in the loan approval criteria.', question:'What should the PM do?', options:['Implement the feature as specified since it meets the functional requirements','Escalate the ethics committee\'s concerns as a legitimate project risk: engage domain experts to assess algorithmic bias risk (demographic impact analysis), engage legal/compliance on regulatory requirements (fair lending laws), involve the ethics committee in acceptance criteria development, and ensure the feature design explicitly addresses bias detection and mitigation before implementation.','Defer the ethics concern to the data science team and continue implementation','Implement the feature and address bias concerns in a post-implementation audit'], correct:1, explanation:'Algorithmic bias in loan decisions has serious regulatory (Fair Lending Act, Equal Credit Opportunity Act), ethical, and reputational consequences. The PM must treat the ethics committee\'s concern as a legitimate stakeholder input that creates project risk. Responsible AI/ML deployment requires: bias impact assessment (does the model produce disparate outcomes across demographic groups?), regulatory compliance verification, explicit bias detection mechanisms, and stakeholder-agreed acceptance criteria for fairness. "Works as specified" is insufficient for algorithmic systems with societal impact. Implementing first and auditing later is a post-harm governance approach. The PM\'s role is to integrate ethical requirements into project design, not route around them.' },
  { domain:'Business Environment', scenario:'A project manager is closing a project. The sponsor\'s organization is undergoing a major reorganization, and the primary sponsor has been reassigned. The new organizational leadership is unfamiliar with the project\'s objectives.', question:'What should the project manager do to ensure successful project closure?', options:['Close the project as quickly as possible before new leadership questions the project','Identify and engage the new leadership as the new sponsor group: brief them on project objectives, accomplishments, and remaining closure activities; obtain their formal acceptance of deliverables; ensure the benefits realization plan is transferred to appropriate operations owners; and complete all governance documentation.','Proceed with closure under the original sponsor\'s authority since they authorized the project','Cancel the project closure since organizational continuity is broken'], correct:1, explanation:'Organizational change mid-project is an EEF risk that requires stakeholder re-engagement, not procedural shortcuts. New leadership inheriting a project they don\'t understand cannot make informed acceptance decisions or govern the benefits realization phase. The PM must: brief new leaders substantively on the project\'s purpose and status, establish a new sponsorship relationship, obtain informed formal acceptance (not rubber-stamp acceptance), and transfer benefits realization accountability to the new structure. Rushing closure before questions arise creates the risk of unaccepted deliverables and unowned benefits. Stakeholder continuity through organizational transitions is a PM responsibility.' },
  { domain:'Business Environment', scenario:'A PMO is tracking 25 active projects. The PMO manager asks each PM to report a single RAG (Red/Amber/Green) status for their project. Three PMs report Green while their actual project data shows significant schedule and cost variances.', question:'What systemic problem does this reveal and what should the PMO do?', options:['The RAG system is working — Green means overall the project is fine','The RAG inflation problem: PMs game single-indicator status systems to avoid scrutiny, creating false portfolio health pictures. The PMO should supplement RAG with quantitative data requirements (CPI, SPI values must accompany any Green status), establish threshold-based auto-classification (e.g., CPI < 0.85 = mandatory Yellow), and create a culture where accurate reporting of Amber/Red is valued over persistent Green.','Terminate the three PMs for misrepresenting status','Accept the Green status since PMs have the most accurate view of their projects'], correct:1, explanation:'RAG-only reporting systems are systematically gamed — the social cost of reporting Red or Amber (scrutiny, questions, political exposure) creates incentives for optimistic reporting. The solution requires: (1) Quantitative validation (RAG status must be supported by CPI/SPI/milestone data — Green is not allowed with CPI < 0.85), (2) Automated thresholds (system-flagged status based on data), (3) Cultural change (Amber early is rewarded, Green-that-becomes-Red is penalized). Terminating PMs for a systemic problem they\'re responding rationally to is punishing symptom, not cause. This is portfolio governance design — the PMO\'s core function.' },
];
